<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-01-08T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-01-08T16:00:00-05:00" n="427" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d427">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">823.30/5: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Peru</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Smith</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Lima</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-01-08T16:00:00-05:00"><hi rend="italic">January 8,
                                        1920—4 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received January 9—12:35
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>10. Referring to the Legation’s telegram of November 26, 3 p.m.,<note n="19" xml:id="d427fn19">Not printed.</note> President this morning
                            expressed a desire that the naval affairs commission, which he has
                            requested, be selected and sent to Peru as soon as possible.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Smith</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>